Interesting similarity between Navajo skinwalkers and the Greek Demogorgon in that the name of the creature is itself forbidden and leads to some sort of harm to the breaker of the taboo.

Demogorgon is historically related to Demiurge concept - what does it mean for skinwalkers?

In Navajo myth (it has been mudded a bit with bad horror fiction, I know) a "skinwalker" is a medicine man who has embraced the left-hand path, a shaman fallen into evil.

This is a very Christian concept, in a way. Sin, and specifically pride, leading to man losing his humanity.

So, the skinwalker, he seeks dominance, right? He wants to "transcend" this world, that's what Satan always promises. He obtains great power over the material and psychical world (can change his shape, inflict terror or hypnotize men), but is still confined to this realm, right?

Thus we can establish a faint connection between the two which might explain the similar taboo:

A fallen creature of great worldly power that hates mankind, God, and our world, but unable to escape it (there is no other place!)

I am quite sure no one has ever talked about this.

This is an interesting example of evolutionary theory again not being able to be denied/disproved.

Turns out some crabs are not actually "real crabs" but just "crab-shaped", which means that the "crab shape" happens to be so effective that other animals evolve into having it.

But if it WAS otherwise, then it would still be proof for evolutionary theory being true.

The conclusion would be "All crabs are "real crabs" so they have evolved from the same animal and thus prove evolution is correct"

There is simply no actual way to disprove it using proof.
